<br>
Now, I've not seen the code or anything, but this is what I've surmised from the information that has been provided:<br>
<br>
<br>
For every NPC wandering in Norrath, there is a table called the hate list.  In this table there are several fields including character names, current hate associated with that character, and total damage done.  This table was pretty large to begin with back when it had a limit of like 20 PCs, but then they went and expanded the hate lists of mobs as more raid encounters were added to the game.  This is a pretty fricken huge table to keep a copy of for every mob in the game.<br>
<br>
However, it's important that they keep this table.  It's used not only for calculating XP/looting rights, but for attacking decisions based on weighted agro and proximity, as well as agro logic for mobs 'assisting' their allies.  It's an integral part to NPC actions.<br>
<br>
<br>
On the other hand, what would spending server space on keeping a table like this for PCs get you?  More accurate looting/insignia rights...and not much else.<br>
<br>
<br>
So, the code is probably there, and it's probably viable and not TOO tough to do, but it would mean adding quite a bit of space and processing requirements for the already stressed servers.  I think that's the reason why they won't implement it.  Minimal returns for a significant investment...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
